<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-BSBxELCbhlJm6t_C2ciSEA" name=",_2ys0kL-fEd2e1-cAeXIm5A" guid="-BSBxELCbhlJm6t_C2ciSEA" changeDate="2008-12-01T13:02:25.327+0100">
  <mainDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>For each variability point, define the requirements and criteria to be fulfilled in order to guarantee that the new composit&lt;/SPAN>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>ion is coherent and compatible with the initial requirements and goal. The requirements of the variation points should give enough information to understand the purpose of the variation point and the possible alternatives available. &lt;/SPAN>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt; mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>This information will give a clear idea about the flexibility of the composition. &lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-spacerun: yes&quot;>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/SPAN>The result of this task is the Variation Points Specification, a Service Composition Specification which now contains variation points and information of those variation points to be instantiated and to create the policies which will manage that instantiation. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/P></mainDescription>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgSsHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Explain the reason to include the variation point " guid="_UBUgSsHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>It is important to know the role of each possible variation point in the composition. This is why it has been included, the type of functionality related with it and the alternatives available. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>For each variation point identified, explain why it is important to include this variation point and the dynamicity the composition will gain with it. This will give the arguments to decide the variation points to be implemented and those to be discarded. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>This step can be done gathering the information collected in the previous task, doing an analysis of those data having in mind costs and benefits, and writing the conclusions. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgTMHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Define context information needed as input " guid="_UBUgTMHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>To instantiate a variation point with a real service, a decision must be taken. And that decision is based in the data collected before taking it. It is very important to indicate the information which will determine the alternative that will be selected in the instantiation of the variation point, because the composition must be able to provide it. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>For each variation point, having in account the types of alternatives, analyse selection criteria. This means identifying the conditions which will determine when to select one alternative or another one. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>Then, identify the input data needed to evaluate those conditions. The information could be very different depending on the condition, so try to identify clearly the data structures as well.&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-spacerun: yes&quot;>&amp;nbsp; &lt;/SPAN>&lt;/FONT>&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgS8HrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Define the functionalities and kinds of alternatives for the variation point " guid="_UBUgS8HrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>This is a general description of the functionality the variation point contains, and the kind of alternatives which may be available for that variation point (examples of alternatives). Use all the information generated in previous tasks and steps.&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-spacerun: yes&quot;>&amp;nbsp; &lt;/SPAN>&lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>Analyse the impact in non functional requirements of the overall composition. This will allow identifying if there would be an important impact in the rest of the composition and if there are some special requirements to be taken in account. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>The information should be as accurate as possible, to facilitate the description of policies and an effective search of services for the alternatives. This means that it is important to clarify the differences between the alternatives. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>Note: Before this step, some variation points may be discarded if their implementation would be too complex or if it is clear that they are not very important for the composition. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgTcHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Check the consistency with the original design " guid="_UBUgTcHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN lang=ES-TRAD style=&quot;FONT-SIZE: 10pt&quot;>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>At this point, the composition design may have been changed. In this task the new design has to be checked to guarantee that applied changes have not altered main goal of the composition in a negative way, as well as non functional requirements such as security or transactions management. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
